Junior\nl Order United American Meehan\nin*. September 26, at St. James\nEpiscopal Church, Thirty-fourth\nst. and Rainier Ave., Mt. Ramer.\n1 The committee in charge of af\nfairs is headed by Vice Councilor\nA. S. Bovey. who will have the as\nsistance of the Daughters of\nAmerica.\nMother of Gibson\nTo Be Buried Today\nLOS ANGELES. Calif\u201e Sept. 15\n(INJS.).\u2014Mrs. Prank A. Gibson,\nmother of Ambassador Hugh\nGibson, will be burled this after\nnoon. it was announced yesterday.\nGibson is hurrying here from\nhis poet at Brussels. Belgium, but\nis not expected to reach Los\nAngeles in time for the funeral.\nMrs. Gibson died Thursday.\na\nThe Metises! Daffy\nGas Rate Hearing\nSet for Wednesday\nRevised drafts of the Washing\nton Gas Light Company\u2019s pro\nposed new rate schedules will be\nconsidered by the Public Utilities\nCommission at a public hearing at\nthe District Building Wednesday\nmorning.\nThe schedule was revised to cor\nrect errors in the first draft filed\nwith the commission.\nMONO AT, SEPTEMBER 18, 1080\nGilpin Estate Given\nr Common Law IWife\nTRENTON, Bept. 15. \u2014A dis\npute between the legal and the\ncommon law wives over the\n$2,500 estate of Charles S. Gilpin,\nnegro actor, who rose to fame\nin The Emperor Jones, was settled\nwhen Judge A. O. Robbins in Mer\ncer county orphans\u2019 court\nawarded- hah of the estate to\nAlma Bynum, Gilpin\u2019s common\nlaw wife, and the other half to\nhis son, Paul, of Philadelphia.\nTheater Censorship\nDefended by Critic\nPARIB, Sept. 15 (INB.).\u2014The\npublic is protected from vice and\nfolly iby censorship, according to\nGeorge de la FDuchardiere, prom\ninent critic here. There should be\na dictatorship over the plans and\nmoving pictures presented to the\nworld at large, he believes. The\nfree exhibition of anything pro\nduced on th estage or screen is a\ncrime against humanity, he holds,\nand should be strictly limited.\nTn Ml this MW ter Mm &tmt\n\u25a0mm far IM tetMt la WrtMtt\nmite.\nDAN6IM